Thought for 28 seconds

We are designing a website for Mallorca Property Partners (MPP), a real estate brokerage targeting Silicon Valley/San Francisco buyers. The website must cater to three customer segments (Operators, Builders, Sovereigns) and offer two distinct paths: Transactional (self-serve) and Full Integration (white-glove). The design should be clean, fast, and trust-focused, avoiding luxury clichés and using concrete data and documents.

We have a vision document that outlines the company's core values and operating principles. We'll now focus on the website description, incorporating the key concepts.

Key elements from the vision document:

  • Dual leadership (American and Mallorcan co-founders)

  • Two service paths: Transactional and Full Integration

  • Three customer segments with different needs

  • Trust signals: transparency, speed, local partnerships (Servera and Salvà)

  • Compliance and cultural respect

Website goals:

  1. Convey trust and transparency.

  2. Allow users to choose their path (Transactional or Full Integration) early.

  3. Provide detailed, verifiable information for each property.

  4. Facilitate quick contact via WhatsApp (preferred by target audience).

  5. Showcase the team's dual heritage and local partnerships.

We'll describe the website structure and key pages, focusing on user experience and design elements that reflect the company's values.

Let's break down the website:

  1. Homepage

    • Clear value proposition.

    • Toggle switch for Transactional vs. Full Integration mode (changes the site's focus).

    • Trust badges (Colegio license, in-house legal team, 24h WhatsApp response).

    • No stock photos; use real images of documents, maps, and the team.

  2. Transactional Path

    • Property listings with detailed data (title status, water rights, coordinates, etc.).

    • Due Diligence Pack download for each property.

    • WhatsApp contact for transaction manager (ex-Google PM).

    • Fee calculator and transparent pricing.

  3. Full Integration Path

    • Description of the white-glove service (residency, school placement, staff vetting, community integration).

    • Calendly link for a call with the American co-founder.

    • Integration Scorecard example.

    • Testimonials from current clients (with proof of authenticity).

  4. Team Page

    • Photos and bios of both co-founders, emphasizing their dual heritage and expertise.

    • Introduction to Servera and Salvà, with their roles and equity stakes (trust signal).

    • LinkedIn profiles and verifiable credentials.

  5. Partners Page

    • Logos and descriptions of key partners (Pérez-Llorca, local mayors, etc.).

    • Explanation of the anti-gentrification protocol (local home repairs).

  6. Contact Page

    • Primary contact via WhatsApp (floating button on every page).

    • Secondary contact form (for those who prefer email).

    • Physical address in Palma (with photo of the office).

  7. Property Pages

    • For each property, provide:

      • Real photos (no staging, with captions including location and date).

      • Key data in monospace font (coordinates, water rights, title status).

      • GIS map showing buildable areas and protected zones.

      • Downloadable Due Diligence Pack (title deed, water rights certificate, etc.).

      • Two CTAs: one for Transactional (download pack, WhatsApp) and one for Full Integration (schedule a call).

Design elements:

  • Color palette: Navy (#0f172a), Slate (#1e293b), Cyan (#0ea5e9) for transactional, Purple (#8b5cf6) for integration.

  • Typography: Inter for body, JetBrains Mono for data points.

  • Imagery: Real documents, GIS maps, team photos, local partners at work.

We'll now write a detailed description of the website, focusing on the user journey and key design decisions.

A dual-path website that instantly segments users into either Transactional or Full Integration buyers, then delivers tailored experiences for each. The design must feel like Y Combinator meets Mallorcan heritage - no luxury clichés, only verifiable truth.

CONTACT ARCHITECTURE

Contact Flow Decision Tree

text
User Action → System Response
──────────────────────────────────────────────────
1. Clicks "WhatsApp" on property page
   → Opens WhatsApp with pre-filled message:
     "Interested in [Property ID]. Send DD pack."

2. Clicks "Schedule Integration Call"
   → Opens Calendly with:
     - 15-min slots with American co-founder
     - Required: LinkedIn profile URL
     - Pre-call questionnaire (budget, timeline, family size)

3. Downloads Due Diligence Pack
   → Email follow-up in 24h:
     "Did the documents answer your questions?
     WhatsApp our transaction manager for next steps."

4. Visits Verification Center > 2 minutes
   → Popup: "Need help verifying documents?
     Our legal team is available via WhatsApp."

ANTI-PATTERNS (WHAT WE DON'T DO)

Design Forbidden Elements

❌ No "luxury" aesthetics

  • No gold accents

  • No marble backgrounds

  • No serif fonts for body text

❌ No lifestyle photography

  • No sunset beaches

  • No yacht shots

  • No staged family dinners

  • No drone flyovers

❌ No vague claims

  • No "breathtaking views" without elevation data

  • No "prime location" without zoning maps

  • No "turnkey" without habitation license numbers

❌ No slow elements

  • No video backgrounds

  • No image carousels

  • No parallax scrolling

  • No animated transitions

SUCCESS METRICS BUILT INTO DESIGN

Trackable Conversion Points

  1. Due Diligence Pack downloads (Transactional intent)

  2. Integration Calendly bookings (White-glove intent)

  3. WhatsApp conversations initiated (High-intent engagement)

  4. Document Vault time spent (Trust building)
